25|$|In early 1920s Russia, Oleg Losev was {{experimenting with}} {{applying}} voltage biases to {{various kinds of}} crystals for manufacture of radio detectors. The result was astonishing: with a zincite (zinc oxide) crystal he gained amplification. This was <b>negative</b> <b>resistance</b> phenomenon, decades before {{the development of the}} tunnel diode. After the first experiments, Losev built regenerative and superheterodyne receivers, and even transmitters.|$|E
25|$|A {{lighting}} ballast is {{a device}} to provide proper starting and operating electrical conditions to light one or more fluorescent lamps, while also limiting the amount of current. A familiar and widely used example is the traditional inductive ballast used in fluorescent lamps, to limit the current through the tube, which would otherwise rise to destructive levels due to the tube's <b>negative</b> <b>resistance</b> characteristic. A disadvantage of using an inductor is that current is shifted out of phase with the voltage, producing a poor power factor.|$|E
